node.text:
This Asian Pacific Islander Heritage Month, our API community is sharing how their heritage inspires their creativity. Hear @the.korean.vegan’s powerful reflections on her grandmother and share your work with the hashtag #OurDearElders for a chance to be featured.

"I’ve partnered with @adobe to honor #OurDearElders, and today, I honor my grandmother. My brave, ferocious, loving grandmother. Who slipped out of North Korea through swamp water and cut through the mountains on foot, all while keeping my father safe. Tell me, how do you honor your elders? How have their stories shaped you? What are some of the foods you like to eat in remembrance of those who came before you? Share how you honor them with #OurDearElders so that we can all join in on this beautiful discussion." - Joanne Molinaro

node.text:
Derived from rich and diverse roots, the Hispanic culture reflects the stories of challenges, triumph, and resilience. Illustrator Dia Pacheco embraces her vibrant culture by sharing its traditions and tales through her work. 

Celebrate the start of #HispanicHeritageMonth and discover how the hues of @diapachecoo's culture inspire her illustrations in this week's #WomenCreateWednesday.

node.text:
Art that educates, inspires, and informs has the power to change our world for the better. 🌎 ❤️

We collaborated with artists like @phingpit to use their artistic talents to #CreateForGood and inspire change on matters important to them.

“There are many ways to preserve our environment so we’ve decided that we should help each other spread the knowledge. This could be learning about burning forests and inspiring change or as simple as doing more at home to protect the planet. We can consume less electricity, reduce waste plastic and turn to canvas bags, which you can always reuse! Easy? Isn’t it. These small things can help our world be a better place.“- @phingpit
